John the Ripper
Fast password cracker for offline hash cracking

Password Attacks
Description
John the Ripper is a free and open-source password security auditing and password recovery tool. It can crack various password hash types and is highly customizable with different attack modes.

Installation / Check
Check if installed:

which john
Install command:

sudo apt install john
Basic Syntax
john [options] <password-file>
Common Commands
Command	What it does	When to use	Risk
john hashes.txt

Auto-detect - John detects hash type	Quick start cracking	
john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt hashes.txt

Dictionary attack - Use wordlist	Common passwords	
john --show hashes.txt

Show cracked - Display results	View cracked passwords	
john --format=raw-md5 hashes.txt

Specify format - Set hash type	Known hash format	
john --incremental hashes.txt

Brute force - All combinations	Exhaustive search	
john --incremental=digits hashes.txt

Digits only - Numeric passwords	PIN cracking	
unshadow /etc/passwd /etc/shadow > combined.txt

Combine passwd/shadow - Linux passwords	Linux system passwords	
john --rules --wordlist=wordlist.txt hashes.txt

Rules mode - Apply mangling rules	Password variations	
john --fork=4 --wordlist=wordlist.txt hashes.txt

Multi-process - Use 4 CPU cores	Speed up cracking	
john --session=mycrack hashes.txt

Named session - Save progress	Long crack sessions	
john --restore=mycrack

Restore session - Continue cracking	Resume interrupted	
john --format=nt hashes.txt

NTLM hashes - Windows passwords	Windows SAM hashes	
john --format=raw-sha256 hashes.txt

SHA256 hashes - Modern hashes	SHA256 passwords	
john --format=bcrypt hashes.txt

bcrypt hashes - Strong hashing	bcrypt passwords	
john --format=zip encrypted.zip

ZIP password - Crack encrypted ZIP	Protected archives	
john --format=rar encrypted.rar

RAR password - Crack encrypted RAR	RAR archives	
john --format=pdf document.pdf

PDF password - Crack protected PDF	Encrypted PDF files	
john --format=office document.docx

Office password - MS Office files	Protected documents	
john --list=formats

List formats - Show supported hashes	Check format support	
john --list=rules

List rules - Show mangling rules	View rule sets	
john --mask=?d?d?d?d hashes.txt

Mask attack - Pattern-based	Known pattern (4 digits)	
john --mask=?u?l?l?l?d?d?d?s hashes.txt

Complex mask - Upper+lower+digits+special	Complex patterns	
john --pot=custom.pot hashes.txt

Custom potfile - Separate results	Project separation	
john --external=filter hashes.txt

External mode - Custom C filters	Advanced filtering	
zip2john encrypted.zip > ziphash.txt

Extract ZIP hash - Get hash from ZIP	Prepare ZIP for crack	
rar2john encrypted.rar > rarhash.txt

Extract RAR hash - Get hash from RAR	Prepare RAR for crack	
pdf2john.pl document.pdf > pdfhash.txt

Extract PDF hash - Get hash from PDF	Prepare PDF for crack	
Step-by-Step Guide
1
Obtain password hashes (legally!)
2
Identify the hash type if possible
3
Run john with a wordlist: john --wordlist=wordlist.txt hashes.txt
4
Wait for results - can take seconds to days
5
Check progress: press any key while running
6
View cracked passwords: john --show hashes.txt
7
Results are saved in ~/.john/john.pot
Understanding the Output
John shows: username:password format for cracked passwords. Progress shows candidates per second and time estimates. Use --show to see all cracked passwords.

Important Warnings
•
Only crack passwords you own or have permission to audit
•
Cracking stolen password hashes is illegal
•
Hash cracking can take very long for strong passwords
•
This is an offline tool - doesn't attack live systems
⚠️ Use Kali Linux tools only on systems you own or have written permission to test. Unauthorized hacking is illegal and can result in criminal charges.
